<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-780-226  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 780 226.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Information Executive  Summer 1990 v3 n3 p14(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>CASE: the reality of current utilization. (computer aided/assistedsoftware/system engineering)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Hughes, Cary; Clark, Jeff.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>CASE is not widely used but more MIS managers are considering it.andO;There are four types of CASE products: upper CASE, which turns acompany's strategic plan into an architecture made up of data,applications, and geographic hardware platforms; middle CASE,which automates the front-end analysis and design activities ofthe system development life cycle (SDLC); lower CASE, whichautomates the physical design and implementation activities of theSDLC; and I-CASE, integrated CASE tools that handle the entirelife cycle.andP;  A survey of 1,000 data processing managers brought128 responses.andP;  The survey shows over two-thirds do not currentlyuse CASE tools, CASE is used more in large firms, andmanufacturing uses CASE more than service industries such asbanking and insurance.andP;  Financial reasons were cited as the numberone reason for not using CASE with lack of knowledge about CASE asthe second.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     SurveyCompaniesComputer-Aided Software EngineeringManagement of EDPProject Life CycleTrends.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Case utilization. (table)Length of service in firms and Case utilization. (table)Firm revenue and Case utilization. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>